      "url": "https://www.instagram.com/reel/Cq8L7h5IWnM/",
      "caption": "This scene is so beautiful, it represents the untamed elements that exist within us all, and the fear and awe we have of those parts of ourselves. Here, the fox represents the cultured, civilised part of ourselves, the wolf the unbridled and untethered. Neither part is right, wrong, or avoidable. They both just are.\n\nBelow is the original caption from @cinephile.club Director Wes Anderson said of this scene “There were some people who didn’t like the wolf scene. In particular one very important person. And he said, I don’t understand what this scene is doing in the movie. And I would always say to him, I’m not cutting it. That scene is why I’m making the movie.”\n\nIn “Fantastic Mr.Fox” the Wolf, being the representation of pure wildness, cannot speak English (or French, or even Latin ). The black wolf is intended to be a metaphor for Mr. Fox’s internal shadow and is a representation of the wild. It is a connection between civilization and wildness."
