      "caption": "In September 2008, the FT’s John Gapper wrote that the US government should resist saving Lehman Brothers. Within days, his advice (and that of others) was taken, triggering a postwar financial crisis and unleashing economic and social damage that still endures today. •\n\nHere are his thoughts on the column 10 years later: 'No bank should have had the right to expect, or to demand, salvation. \nBut none of this, nor my self-justification in 2010 that letting Lehman fold had been “a gamble worth taking”, gets me off the hook. My argument was about more than the fate of one foolish bank. It covered all of Wall Street’s investment banks and trading institutions apart from retail banks. \nWhat strikes me now is less my wrongness than my naivety. I hoped and believed — implausibly, given that barriers between commercial and investment banks had been weakened by changes in US law and mergers — that investment banks were still small and separate enough to collapse without precipitating a crisis.' Read more at FT.com\n\nIllustration by Ingram Pinn\n\n#FT #FinancialTimes #financialcrisis #johngapper #column #2008 #financialcrisis #ingrampinn"
