      "url": "https://www.instagram.com/p/DWkHAZFAnCw/",
      "caption": "The InterContinental Railway (ICR), also known as the Trans-Eurasian Belt Development (TEPR), is a massive infrastructure proposal designed to create a continuous land link between North America and Europe. \n\nIntroduced by Vladimir Yakunin in 2015, the project envisions a multi-modal transportation corridor featuring a high-speed railway, oil and gas pipelines, and fiber optic cables. The centerpiece of the plan is a tunnel beneath the Bering Strait, which would technically consist of two 35-mile sections connecting through the Diomede Islands.\n\n​To make this vision a reality, the project requires the construction of approximately 5,500 miles of new track across some of the world's most difficult terrain. In Russia, this would involve extending the Trans-Siberian Railway from its current eastern reaches through the remote Chukotka region. On the American side, it would necessitate building a rail corridor through the Alaskan wilderness and across Canada to link with the existing U.S. rail network. \n\nWhile the engineering is theoretically possible, the estimated costs—exceeding $100 billion for the tunnel alone—and shifting geopolitical relations remain the primary obstacles to its commencement."
